intro: Alsine setacea subsp. leucocephaloides, commonly known as the white-headed alsike, is a flowering plant belonging to the family Caryophyllaceae. It is characterized by its prostrate growth habit and small, white to pale pink flowers that bloom in late spring. The plant typically has hairy stems and leaves with a narrow, linear shape. It is native to parts of Europe and is often found in sandy or disturbed soils. This subspecies is noted for its ornamental value and is sometimes cultivated in gardens.
